Question 7.5.9 (Approximate Subgradient Method with Diminishing Stepsize)

Dual function: mu^{k+1} = [mu^k + (s*g)^k]+

Subgradient: sum_k=0_infinity[s^k] = infinity

             (s*||g^2||)^k -> 0

             eta^k >= 0

             eta^k -> 0

a) Lemma: A lower and upper bound presents itself in a subgradient method

Proof by Equivalence:

   Proof by Deduction:

     Hypothesis: ||mu^{k+1}- mu*||^2 <= ||mu^k-mu*||^2 - 2*s^k*(q(mu)-q(mu^k) - eta^k) + (s^k)^2*||g^k||^2

     Outcome: q(mu^k) <= sup{q(mu)} - eta 

                 lim(k->inf)sup{q(mu^k)} <= sup{q(mu)}

   Proof by Deduction:

     Hypothesis: The limit of eta^k approaches zero

     Outcome: sup[q(mu)] - eta <= lim(k->inf)sup{q(mu^k)} <= sup q(mu)

b) Lemma: lim(k->inf)sup{q(mu^k)} = sup{q(mu)}

   Proof by Deduction:
  
     Hypothesis: sum_k=0_infinity[s^k] = infinity

                 (s*||g^2||)^k -> infinity

     Outcome:  2*s^k*(q(mu)-q(mu^k) - eta^k) + ||mu^{k+1}- mu*||^2 <= ||mu^k-mu*||^2 + (s^k)^2*||g^k||^2

               infinity + ||mu^{k+1}- mu*||^2 <= ||mu^k-mu*||^2  + infinity

               lim(k->inf)sup{q(mu^k)} = sup{q(mu)}
